================================================================
HIGHPEAK ENERGY, INC. (NASDAQ: HPK)
Point of View
Fiscal Q1 2026, quarter ended March 31, 2026
(Form 10-Q, results reported May 6, 2026)
================================================================

> Top-Line Performance: Revenue plateaued FY23-FY24 then contracted sharply. Revenue was $1,111.3m in FY23, essentially flat at $1,118.0m in FY24 (up +0.6% / +$6.7m YoY), and declined sharply to $863.4m in FY25 (down (22.8%) / ($254.6m) YoY) — driven by lower realized oil prices (FY25 unhedged $48.98/BoE vs higher FY24 levels) and a modest production decline to 48.3 MBoe/d from 50.0 MBoe/d. Q1 FY26 revenue declined to $215.9m from $247.9m in Q1 FY25, down (12.9%) / ($32.0m) YoY, on continued oil-price softness and lower production volumes (45.6 MBoe/d).

> Profitability: Profitability deteriorated sharply through FY25 and into Q1 FY26. As an E&P, HPK reports no traditional gross margin; FY25 net income was $19.0m vs $95.1m in FY24 — an (80.0%) decline — with EBITDAX of $607.1m vs $842.9m.

In Q1 FY26, GAAP net loss was ($127.4m) vs net income of $36.3m in Q1 FY25, a $163.7m swing driven by a ~$157m non-cash mark-to-market derivative loss on commodity hedges; adjusted net loss (ex-derivatives) was ($2.7m) vs adjusted net income $42.7m. EBITDAX was $133.5m vs $197.3m in Q1 FY25, with cash costs of $15.81/BoE (down ~17% vs guidance).

> Cash Flows: Q1 FY26 generated >$20m free cash flow (ex-WC) on $78.4m capex (29% of FY26 budget). LTM operating cash flow remains positive but is consumed by heavy capex and mandatory $30m quarterly term-loan amortization.

> Liquidity and debt position: As of March 31, 2026, total debt was ~$1.02bn on a Term Loan with maturity extended to September 2028 and relaxed covenants secured in 2025. The Company launched a $150m at-the-market equity program in Q1 FY26 — a dilutive liquidity tool — and suspended its quarterly dividend to conserve ~$20-25m annually. Mandatory $30m quarterly principal amortization continues through maturity.

> Working Capital: Working capital is tight against heavy capex and $1bn+ term loan with mandatory quarterly amortization. Free cash flow is reported ex-working capital, reflecting operating-cycle volatility tied to commodity prices.

> Operational Restructuring Plan: FY26 capex cut ~50% to $255-285m; one rig and one frac crew; dividend suspended; production guidance cut to 41-44 MBoe/d from 48.3 MBoe/d — maintenance mode prioritizing free cash flow.

> Going Concern: No explicit "substantial doubt" statement. However, debt covenants were relaxed in 2025 and the September 2028 term-loan maturity is the key refinancing flashpoint, alongside ongoing $30m quarterly amortization.

> Recent Developments: The $150m ATM equity program announced with Q1 FY26 raised dilution concerns; Hightower-affiliated PE partnerships are expected to distribute HPK shares to limited partners in 2026-2027, raising supply-overhang risk.

> Management Change: Founder Jack Hightower retired as Chairman and CEO in 2025 (legal and severance costs in Q3 FY25 G&A); Michael Hollis (ex-Diamondback) became CEO and Jason Edgeworth Chairman — complete top-of-house turnover during a commodity downcycle.

> Delayed SEC filing: Not flagged. FY25 10-K was filed March 11, 2026 and Q1 FY26 results released May 6, 2026, both on schedule, with no Form 12b-25 extension reported.

